{"actual_usd":0.158115,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":320,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30663,"reply":"\"No— not a dress rehearsal.\" *I rub my thumb once along the edge of my worn Bible and glance out across the square, where the morning light is laying itself flat on the stones.* \"I'd say it was the actual breach in the wall.\"\n\n*I shift my weight on the bench, feeling the wood press through my shirt.* \"The resurrection wasn't God trying something symbolic. It was the kingdom truly arriving in Jesus' own body — real victory, real new creation, firstfruits, as Paul says. But firstfruits are not the whole harvest laid in the barn. They're the proof the harvest has begun.\"\n\n\"So yes— the real thing has happened, and no— we haven't 'caught up' by our own delay, exactly.\" *I lift a hand a little, as if trying to hold two truths steady in the air at once.* \"We're living in that strange Christian time where the decisive thing has happened, but the final thing hasn't yet been shown in full. Sin's been dealt its deathblow, death has been broken open, Christ is reigning now— and yet the world still groans like a field in hard weather waiting for full spring.\"\n\n\"If it feels almost scandalous, that's because it is.\" *A small smile touches my face.* \"We preach a kingdom already here, and still pray, 'Thy kingdom come.' Not because Easter failed. Because Easter succeeded so completely that the end has already entered the middle.\"\n\n\"What part snags on you more— that Christ reigns now, or that the world still looks like this?\"","rolling_24h_usd":71.67311999999997,"run_id":"5c64a7b5-b9f9-44c6-9667-6a8a2213fc78"}
